  "text": "The amount of metabolically active tissue accounts in part for how much oxygen a person can utilize. Our studies in stroke confirm a strong relationship between thigh muscle mass, as measured by dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry (DEXA), and peak aerobic capacity. [CITATION_1] VO 2 peak was related to the lean muscle mass of both thighs (r ϭ 0.64, p Ͻ 0.001), with lean mass predicting Ͼ40% of the variance in peak aerobic fitness. [CITATION_2] CT scans of the paretic midthigh show 20% less muscle area than the nonparetic thigh (p Ͻ 0.0001). In addition, intramuscular fat is 25% greater in the paretic thigh than the nonparetic thigh (p Ͻ 0.0001). [CITATION_3] Elevated intramuscular fat may be associated with insulin resistance and its complications [CITATION_4] and has relevance to cardiovascular fitness and function. [CITATION_5] ",
